[33mcommit 88c8e4b3ee83eee3cb26c49ccc16e7ea620f4562[m
Author: Shimwoojin <ggoggal@gmail.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 11:55:57 2026 +0900

    fix: defer actor destroy + harden Octree against dangling pointers
    
    Recurring crash in FOctree::RemoveDirect during meteor / police phases
    came from two compounding lifetime issues:
    
    1. World::DestroyActor was synchronously calling delete during PhysX
       onContact callbacks (police HandleHit -> EndPhase -> DespawnPoliceCars
       -> DestroyActor on this and its siblings) and during actor self-tick
       (meteor lifetime expiry). The actor's "this" survived those callbacks
       only by luck; one frame later the Octree saw stale pointers.
    
    2. UPrimitiveComponent caches its current FOctree* in OctreeNode. Merges
       triggered from RemoveSinglePrimitive could free nodes mid-frame, and
       the next FlushPrimitive would dereference the dangling pointer in
       RemoveDirect's std::find -- the actual crash site.
    
    Fixes:
    
    UObjectManager:
    - Add MarkPendingKill / IsPendingKill / FlushPendingKill. World::DestroyActor
      finishes its synchronous partition / level / picking-BVH cleanup as before
      but enqueues the actual delete via MarkPendingKill. UEngine::Tick calls
      FlushPendingKill after WorldTick + Render so the delete happens at a
      point where no callback is mid-flight on the actor.
    - DestroyObject stays as immediate delete so destructor-time cleanups
      (~AActor::RemoveComponent, transient material releases) still run inline.
    
    UObject alive tracking:
    - New TSet<UObject*> GUObjectSet maintained by UObject ctor / dtor for
      O(1) liveness lookup. New global IsValid(const UObject*) is safe to
      call on dangling pointers (hash compare only, no deref).
    - IsAliveObject is now an alias for IsValid.
    
    Octree:
    - RemoveDirect, TryMerge, ClearChildrenAndPrimitiveLocations, and
      GetAllPrimitives all filter PrimitiveList entries through IsValid before
      touching them, so a stale pointer in some node's list cannot poison the
      merge that re-parents primitives.
    
    SpatialPartition:
    - FlushPrimitive and RemoveSinglePrimitive no longer use the cached
      Prim->GetOctreeNode() pointer (which can point to a freed FOctree).
      They go through Octree->Remove which traverses from the root, slightly
      slower but immune to dangling node pointers.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

