    Cause: ProcessPendingTransition runs DestroyWorldContext +
    LoadSceneFromPath + World->BeginPlay all inside one frame's tail
    end. The next FEngineLoop iteration calls Timer.Tick(), which
    measures elapsed time from the *previous* Timer.Tick — which now
    includes the entire load duration. The first frame after a
    transition therefore hands a 1–3s dt to UWorld::Tick →
    PhysicsScene->Tick → PxScene->simulate(dt). Big single PhysX step
    tunnels through static geometry, so on the first Intro→Map entry
    the car drops through the map. Second entry is fast (mesh/texture
    caches warm) so the dt spike is small enough to be invisible.
    
    Fix: at the end of ProcessPendingTransition call
    GetTimer()->Initialize(), which sets LastTime = now. The next
    Timer.Tick produces a normal frame-interval dt instead of "frame +
    load time". Startup load was already covered because FEngineLoop::
    Init calls Timer.Initialize *after* GEngine->BeginPlay; only the
    runtime transition path was missing this.
    
