    fix: gate PostEditProperty's PhysX register by bComponentHasBegunPlay
    
    Standalone Game scene-load registered each PrimitiveComponent's PhysX
    body with default values (mass=1, BoxExtent=1×1×1, ObjectType=
    WorldStatic, COM=zero) instead of the values saved in the .Scene file,
    so the car body PhysX was a unit cube of mass 1 sitting at z=2.6 — no
    ground contact for the wheel raycast, no movement.
    
    Root cause: DeserializeProperties iterates the GetEditableProperties
    descriptor list in order and fires Obj->PostEditProperty after each
    field is set. UPrimitiveComponent's "Collision Enabled" PostEdit
    unconditionally calls World->GetPhysicsScene()->RegisterComponent —
    but the iteration hits "Collision Enabled" before "Object Type",
    "Mass (kg)", "Center Of Mass Offset", "Box Extent", etc. So the body
    gets created with whatever those fields' defaults are, and every
    later setter (SetMass, SetBoxExtent, …) goes through
    NotifyPhysicsBodyDirty which is already guarded by
    !bComponentHasBegunPlay return — so none of the later changes
    propagate to PhysX. BeginPlay's RegisterComponent then short-circuits
    on "already mapped".
    
    PIE doesn't hit this: DuplicateAs roundtrips properties through
    Serialize without invoking PostEditProperty, then BeginPlay registers
    once with everything already set.
    
    Fix mirrors the same guard SetCollisionEnabled already has — return
    early when !bComponentHasBegunPlay so the first registration happens
    at PrimitiveComponent::BeginPlay with all fields in their final state,
    matching the PIE timing. The runtime case (editor property panel
    flipping the enum after BeginPlay) still works because the guard
    passes once bComponentHasBegunPlay is true.
    
